	<p style="font-size: 150%;">
		<strong>Components of a rainwater harvesting system</strong>
	</p>

	<p style="font-size: 150%;">A rainwater harvesting set-up is
		composed of a water-collection system, a storage cistern and a water
		distribution system. It mainly needs:</p>
	<p style="font-size: 150%;"> *. Rain, and plenty of it preferably</p> 
	<p style="font-size: 150%;"> *. A catchment area</p> 
	<p style="font-size: 150%;"> *. Gutters or pipes </p>
	<p style="font-size: 150%;"> *. Storage tank</p> 
	<p style="font-size: 150%;"> *. Filter (can be a simple metal screen filter or slow
		  sand filter or even more sophisticated types if required or available)</p>
	<p style="font-size: 150%;"> *. Pump or pressure tank for distribution</p>
	<p style="font-size: 150%;"><strong>Advantages of rain harvesting</strong></p>
	<p style="font-size: 150%;">*. Easily accessible</p>
    <p style="font-size: 150%;">*. Set-up costs are low, with construction easy, materials low-cost and maintenance cheap</p>
    <p style="font-size: 150%;">*. Sustainability is higher</p>
    <p style="font-size: 150%;">*. Easily adaptable to different types of communities</p>
	


